# Reproducing {{ project_name_title }} with Docker + Zenodo

This document explains how **anyone** (with no Python installation) can
reproduce all results and plots from the Zenodo data archive using Docker.

---

## Prerequisites

- [Docker Desktop](https://docs.docker.com/get-started/get-docker/) (macOS / Windows)
  or `docker` + `docker compose` (Linux)
- Internet connection for the one-time image pull and data download

That's it — no Python, no conda, no dependency hell.

---

## Quick Reproduction (3 steps)

### Step 1 — Pull the Docker image from GHCR

```bash
docker pull ghcr.io/YOUR_GITHUB_USERNAME/{{ project_name }}:latest
```

> **Tip**: tag `latest` tracks the most recent published release.
> Pin a specific commit SHA for bit-exact reproducibility:
> `ghcr.io/YOUR_GITHUB_USERNAME/{{ project_name }}:SHA`

### Step 2 — Download data from Zenodo

Visit the Zenodo record (DOI link in the paper / README) and download the
data archive. Then unpack it into a local `data/` directory:

```bash
# Example — replace DOI and filename with your actual values
curl -L "https://zenodo.org/records/YOUR_ZENODO_ID/files/data.tar.gz" -o data.tar.gz
tar -xzf data.tar.gz          # extracts into ./data/
mkdir -p plots                 # output directory
```

### Step 3 — Re-run the analysis

```bash
docker compose run reproduce
```

All generated figures will appear in `./plots/` on your local machine.

---

## What Happens Under the Hood

```
docker compose run reproduce
  │
  ├─ mounts  ./data   → /workspace/data   (read-only)
  ├─ mounts  ./plots  → /workspace/plots  (read-write)
  └─ runs    uv run python scripts/analyze_data.py
             └─ reads  /workspace/data/**/*.h5
             └─ writes /workspace/plots/**/*.pdf  ← appears on your machine
```

The container image contains only code + dependencies — **no data**.
Data stays on your machine and is never baked into the image.

