## Uploading Your Own Data to Zenodo

> Follow these steps when you are ready to publish your own dataset.

1. **Create a Zenodo account** at <https://zenodo.org>
2. **Package your data** — include only what is needed to reproduce results:
   ```bash
   cd my-analysis
   tar -czf data.tar.gz data/sims/ data/exp_pro/
   ```
3. **Create a new upload** on Zenodo:
   - Go to <https://zenodo.org/uploads/new>
   - Upload `data.tar.gz` and any processed files
   - Fill in: title, authors, description, keywords (`reproducibility`, your field)
   - Set access rights (Open Access recommended for reproducibility)
4. **Reserve a DOI** before publishing (Zenodo gives you the DOI upfront)
5. **Add the DOI to your README** and paper so readers can find the data
6. **Publish** — the record is then permanently citable

### What to include in the Zenodo deposit

| Include | Exclude |
|---------|---------|
| Raw experimental data (`data/exp_raw/`) | Raw instrument files if huge (link instead) |
| Processed / simulation output (`data/sims/`, `data/exp_pro/`) | Intermediate scratch files |
| Parameters used (`config/` YAML files) | Virtual environments (`.venv/`) |
| Final plots PDF/SVG | Jupyter checkpoint files |
| `README_DOCKER.md` — this file | `.git/` repository history |

### Linking code and data

Zenodo lets you link to your GitHub repository. This creates a bidirectional
reference between code DOI and data DOI so readers can find both from either
record.

